    Fill in the gaps

    %empty%

    %empty%

      • $60 - \ldots = 43$

        $60 - \underline{\green{17}} = 43$

        $17$

        • $\ldots \times 40 = 280$

          $\underline{\green{7}} \times 40 = 280$

          $7$

          • $\ldots \div 30 = 5$

            $\underline{\green{150}} \div 30 = 5$

            $150$

            • $-8 + \ldots = -1$

              $-8 + \underline{\green{7}} = -1$

              $7$

            aldenham-school--11-plus--maths--2019--sample-paper-1.toml

          • 4624AA36-41A6-4B3C-B4F2-11671F5E0925

            • tnumber

            %empty%

            %empty%

            %empty%

              • $100 \times 2.8 = \ldots$

                $100 \times 2.8 = \underline{\green{280}}$

                $280$

                • $8600 \div 20 = \ldots$

                  $ \begin{aligned} &= 8600 \div 20 \\ &= \dfrac {8600} {20} \\ &= \dfrac {43 \times 2 \times 100} {2 \times 10} \\ &= \dfrac {43 \times \cancel{2} \times 10\cancel{0} } { \cancel{2} \times 1\cancel{0} } \\ &= 43 \times 10 \\ &= 430 \end{aligned} $

                  $430$

                  • $200 \times \ldots = 160$

                    Let the missing value = $a$

                    $ \begin{aligned} 200 \times a &= 160 \\ a &= \dfrac {160} {200} \\ a &= \dfrac {40 \times 4} {40 \times 5} \\ a &= \dfrac { \cancel{40} \times 4} { \cancel{40} \times 5} \\ a &= \dfrac {4} {5} \end{aligned} $

                    $\dfrac {4} {5}$

                  aldenham-school--11-plus--maths--2019--sample-paper-1.toml

                  rag_up_oldpr

                • 5795CBC5-BF94-4D7F-BB5B-55C2F37EC9F2

                  • tnumber

                  Evaluate the following expressions.

                  %empty%

                  %empty%

                    • $13 + 4 \div 2$

                      Using BIDMAS,

                      $ \begin{aligned} &= 13 + 4 \div 2 \\ &= 13 + 2 \\ &= 15 \end{aligned} $

                      $15$

                      • $4 \times 5 - 8 \times 3$

                        Using BIDMAS,

                        $ \begin{aligned} &= 4 \times 5 - 8 \times 3 \\ &= 20 - 24 \\ &= -4 \end{aligned} $

                        $-4$

                        • $(-4 + 7)^3$

                          Using BIDMAS,

                          $ \begin{aligned} &= (-4 + 7)^3 \\ &= (3)^3 \\ &= 27 \end{aligned} $

                          $27$

                      • 269CAEB1-ECC7-4634-9068-42EF39354F2F

                        • ttable
                        • tnumber

                        The table shows the size of population for five Derbyshire villages.

                        VillagePopulation
                        Ashover$1796$
                        Bamford$14320$
                        Clowne$6152$
                        Darley Dale$9517$
                        Eckington$22315$

                        %empty%

                        %empty%

                          • Write the population of Darley Dale in words.

                            Nine thousand five hundred and seventeen

                            Nine thousand five hundred and seventeen

                            • Write the population of Clowne correct to the nearest $100$.

                              Population of Clowne $= 6152$

                              After rounding up to the nearest $100 = 6200$

                              $6200$

                              • Write the population of Eckington to the nearest $1000$.

                                Population of Eckington $= 22315$

                                After rounding down to the nearest $1000 = 22000$

                                $22000$

                                • How many more people live in Eckington than Bamford?

                                  As per the question,

                                  $ \begin{aligned} \text{Difference} &= 22315 - 14320 \\ &= 7995 \end{aligned} $

                                  $7995$

                                                    • 52852CBD-3F19-4E8F-9646-311ABBA46E71

                                                      • tnumber
                                                      • tinfer

                                                      Edith is choosing pairs of numbers from this list.

                                                      $4 \quad 23 \quad 45 \quad 58 \quad 120$

                                                      %empty%

                                                      %empty%

                                                        • She multiplies two numbers together.

                                                          Which two numbers should she choose to get an answer between $200$ and $300$?

                                                          This can be inferred by using trial and error.

                                                          $ \begin{aligned} &= 58 \times 4 \\ &= 232 \end{aligned} $

                                                          $4, 58$

                                                          • She divides one number by another number.

                                                            What is the largest possible answer?

                                                            To get the largest possible answer, we should divide the biggest number by the smallest number.

                                                            $ \begin{aligned} &= 120 \div 4 \\ &= 30 \end{aligned} $

                                                            $30$

                                                          aldenham-school--11-plus--maths--9999--sample-paper-2.toml

                                                          rag_up_oldpr

                                                        • 762E34D3-32F5-4DE3-9383-016936160A92

                                                          • tnumber

                                                          $28450$ people attended a hockey match.

                                                          If $8217$ wore red and $11750$ wore blue, how many wore neither blue nor red?

                                                          $ \begin{aligned} \text{People who wore neither blue nor red} &= 28450 - 8217 - 11750 \\ &= 8483 \end{aligned} $

                                                          $8483$

                                                                                          • $0.309 \quad 0.039 \quad 0.93 \quad 0.093$

                                                                                            $0.309 \quad \boxed{\green{0.039}} \quad 0.93 \quad 0.093$

                                                                                            $0.039$

                                                                                            • $-7.5 \quad -8 \quad 2 \quad 0$

                                                                                              $-7.5 \quad \boxed{\green{-8}} \quad 2 \quad 0$

                                                                                              $-8$

                                                                                              • $\dfrac{1}{5} \quad \dfrac{1}{6} \quad \dfrac{1}{7} \quad \dfrac{1}{8}$

                                                                                                These are all unit fractions. The smallest unit fraction is the one which has the biggest denominator.

                                                                                                $\dfrac{1}{5} \quad \dfrac{1}{6} \quad \dfrac{1}{7} \quad \boxed{\green{\dfrac{1}{8}}}$

                                                                                                $\dfrac{1}{8}$

                                                                                                • $0.4 \quad 30 \% \quad 0.22 \quad \dfrac{1}{4}$

                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} &= 0.4 \quad 30 \% \quad 0.22 \quad \dfrac{1}{4} \\ &= 0.4 \quad 0.3 \quad 0.22 \quad 0.25 \\ &= 0.4 \quad 0.3 \quad \boxed{\green{0.22}} \quad 0.25 \\ &= 0.4 \quad 30 \% \quad \boxed{\green{0.22}} \quad \dfrac{1}{4} \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                  $0.22$

                                                                                                For each question, choose the correct answer

                                                                                                $5000 + ? + 7 = 5087$

                                                                                                • $870$
                                                                                                • $80$
                                                                                                • $87$
                                                                                                • $807$

                                                                                                $ \begin{aligned} 5000 + a + 7 &= 5087 \\ a &= 5087 - 5000 - 7 \\ a &= 80 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                $80$

                                                                                                $2 + (3 \times 6 + 4) \div 2 = ?$

                                                                                                • $17$
                                                                                                • $13$

                                                                                                • $12$

                                                                                                Using BIDMAS,

                                                                                                $ \begin{aligned} &= 2 + (3 \times 6 + 4) \div 2 \\ &= 2 + 22 \div 2 \\ &= 2 + 11 \\ &= 13 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                $13$

                                                                                                    • 25AE63AD-E6BE-469D-8815-36F8E101C78C

                                                                                                      • tnumber

                                                                                                      What is the missing number in this number sentence?

                                                                                                      $3.6 \times {?} = 1.8 \times 7$

                                                                                                      Let the missing number $= a$

                                                                                                      As per the question,

                                                                                                      $ \begin{aligned} 3.6 \times a &= 1.8 \times 7 \\ a &= \dfrac {1.8 \times 7} {3.6} \\ a &= \dfrac {1.8 \times 7} {1.8 \times 2} \\ a &= \dfrac {\cancel {1.8} \times 7} {\cancel {1.8} \times 2} \\ a &= \dfrac {7} {2} \\ a &= 3.5 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                      $3.5$

                                                                                                      alderley-edge-school-for-girls--11-plus--maths--9999--sample-paper-2.toml

                                                                                                      Write the missing numbers in the boxes.

                                                                                                        • $4 \times \boxed{\phantom{555}} + 20 = 180$

                                                                                                          Let the missing value $= a$.

                                                                                                          $ \begin{aligned} 4 \times a + 20 &= 180 \\ 4a &= 180 - 20 \\ 4a &= 160 \\ a &= \dfrac {160} {4} \\ a &= \dfrac {40 \times 4} {4} \\ a &= \dfrac {40 \times \cancel {4}} {\cancel {4}} \\ a &= 40 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                          $40$

                                                                                                          • $4 \times 20 + \boxed{\phantom{555}} = 180$

                                                                                                            Let the missing value $= a$.

                                                                                                            $ \begin{aligned} 4 \times 20 + a &= 180 \\ 80 + a &= 180 \\ a &= 180 - 80 \\ a &= 100
                                                                                                            \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                            $100$

                                                                                                            • $4 \times \boxed{\phantom{555}} - 20 = 180$

                                                                                                              Let the missing value $= a$.

                                                                                                              $ \begin{aligned} 4 \times a - 20 &= 180 \\ 4a &= 180 + 20 \\ 4a &= 200 \\ a &= \dfrac {200} {4} \\ a &= \dfrac {50 \times 4} {4} \\ a &= \dfrac {50 \times \cancel{4}} {\cancel{4}} \\ a &= 50
                                                                                                              \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                              $50$

                                                                                                            alderley-edge-school-for-girls--11-plus--maths--9999--sample-paper-2.toml

                                                                                                                  To find the $n \text{th} \text{ triangular number}$, you can use this rule.

                                                                                                                  $n \text{th} \text{ triangular number} = \dfrac{n}{2}(n + 1)$

                                                                                                                  Example:

                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} 3 \text{rd} \text{ triangular number} &= \dfrac{3}{2} (3 + 1) \ &= 6 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                          • Angus and his six friends have collected $756$ football stickers, which they all share out equally.
                                                                                                                                                            How many stickers do they each get?

                                                                                                                                                            As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                            $ \begin{aligned} \text{Stickers each will get} &= \dfrac {756} {7} \\ &= \dfrac {7 \times 108} {7} \\ &= \dfrac {\cancel{7} \times 108} {\cancel{7}} \\ &= 108 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                            $108

                                                                                                                                                            • Today is Emma's $29 \text{th}$ birthday. How many months old is she?

                                                                                                                                                              As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                              $ \begin{aligned} \text{Months Emma is old} &= 29 \times 12 \\ &= 348 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                              $348$

                                                                                                                                                              • Amar works for $45$ weeks each year. His total cost of travelling to and from work is $\pounds 630$ each year. How much is that per week?

                                                                                                                                                                As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                $ \begin{aligned} \text{Amar's travelling cost per week} &= \dfrac {\pounds 630} {45} \\ &= \dfrac {14 \times 45} {45} \\ &= \dfrac {14 \times \cancel{45}} {\cancel{45}} \\ &= \pounds 14 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                $\pounds 14$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are given two numbers $0.35$ and $\dfrac{5}{8}$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            • Convert $0.35$ into a fraction and simplify fully.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $ \begin{aligned} &= 0.35 \\ &= \dfrac {35} {100} \\ &= \dfrac {7 \times 5} {20 \times 5} \\ &= \dfrac {7 \times \cancel{5}} {20 \times \cancel{5}} \\ &= \dfrac {7} {20} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $\dfrac {7} {20}$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              • Find the sum of these two numbers, write the answer as a fraction in its simplest form.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $ \begin{aligned} &= \dfrac {7} {20} + \dfrac {5} {8} \\ &= \dfrac {7 \times 2} {20 \times 2} + \dfrac {5 \times 5} {8 \times 5} \\ &= \dfrac {14} {40} + \dfrac {25} {40} \\ &= \dfrac {14 + 25} {40} \\ &= \dfrac {39} {40} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $\dfrac {39} {40}$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                • Find the product of these two numbers, write the answer as a fraction in its simplest form.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} &= \dfrac {7} {20} \times \dfrac {5} {8} \\ &= \dfrac {7 \times 5} {20 \times 8} \\ &= \dfrac {7 \times 5} {4 \times 5 \times 8} \\ &= \dfrac {7 \times \cancel {5}} {4 \times \cancel {5} \times 8} \\ &= \dfrac {7} {4 \times 8} \\ &= \dfrac {7} {32}
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $\dfrac {7} {32}$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            Work out the answer to each of these arithmetic problems:

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              • $400 \div 50$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $ \begin{aligned} &= 400 \div 50 \\ &= \dfrac {400} {50} \\ &= \dfrac {8 \times 50} {50} \\ &= \dfrac {8 \times \cancel {50}} {\cancel{50}} \\ &= 8 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $8$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              If $x$ is a number, then $3x$ means "three times $x$"

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                • If $x = 6$, work out the value of $2x$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} &= 2 \times (x) \\ &= 2 \times (6) \\ &= 12 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $12$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  • If $y = 7$, work out the value of $y + 3$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $ \begin{aligned} &= (y) + 3 \\ &= (7) + 3 \\ &= 10 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $10$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    • If $p = 5$ and $q = 3$ work out the value of $3p + 4q$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $ \begin{aligned} &= 3 (p) + 4 (q) \\ &= 3 (5) + 4 (3) \\ &= 15 + 12 \\ &= 27 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $27$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              • tinfer

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              In this question letters of the alphabet are assigned number values:

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $A = 1, B = 2, C = 3, D = 4,$ ....

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              The sum total of a word is created by adding the value of the letters.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              For example: the sum total of ‘$HAD$’ $= 8 + 1 + 4 = 13$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                • What is the sum total of the word ‘$TANK$’?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin {aligned} \text {TANK} &= 20 + 1 + 14 + 11 \\ &= 46 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $46$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  • List the following words in order of their sum total, starting with the lowest:

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $DOG \quad CATS \quad FISH \quad BIRD$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    To compare, let's find the sum first.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $ \begin{aligned} \text {DOG} &= 4 + 15 + 7 \\ &= 26 \text {CATS} &= 3 + 1 + 20 + 19 \\ &= 43 \text {FISH} &= 6 + 9 + 19 + 8 \\ &= 42 \text {BIRD} &= 2 + 9 + 18 + 4 \\ &= 33 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    Let's put them in ascending order now.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $ \begin{aligned} &= 26, \quad 33, \quad 42, \quad 43 \\ &= \text {DOG}, \quad \text {BIRD}, \quad \text {FISH}, \quad \text {CATS} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                Let's make the denominator the same for all the numbers, so we can compare them.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                LCM for $4, 6, 9, 3 = 36$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $ \begin{aligned} &= \dfrac {3} {4}, \quad \dfrac {5} {6}, \quad \dfrac {8} {9}, \quad \dfrac {2}{3} \\ &= \dfrac {3 \times 9} {4 \times 9}, \quad \dfrac {5 \times 6} {6 \times 6}, \quad \dfrac {8 \times 4} {9 \times 4}, \quad \dfrac {2 \times 12} {3 \times 12} \\ &= \dfrac {27} {36}, \quad \dfrac{30} {36}, \quad \dfrac {32} {36}, \quad \dfrac {24} {36} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $\dfrac {32} {36} = \dfrac {8} {9}$ is the biggest.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $\dfrac {8} {9}$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                • Which is biggest?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $\dfrac{1}{4}$ of $21$, $\quad 50\%$ of $11$,$\quad \dfrac{1}{3}$ of $17$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  To compare, let's convert all the numbers to fractions.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} &= \dfrac {1} {4} \ \text {of} \ 21, \quad 50 \% \ \text {of} \ 11, \quad \dfrac {1} {3} \ \text {of} \ 17 \\ &= \dfrac {1} {4} \times 21, \quad \dfrac {50} {100} \times 11, \quad \dfrac {1} {3} \times 17 \\ &= \dfrac {21} {4}, \quad \dfrac {50 \times 11} {100}, \quad \dfrac {17} {3} \\ &= \dfrac {21} {4}, \quad \dfrac {11} {2}, \quad \dfrac {17} {3} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Let's make the denominator the same for all the numbers, so we can compare them.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  LCM for $2, 4, 3 = 12$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} &= \dfrac {21} {4}, \quad \dfrac {11} {2}, \quad \dfrac {17} {3} \\ &= \dfrac {21 \times 3} {4 \times 3}, \quad \dfrac {11 \times 6} {2 \times 6}, \quad \dfrac {17 \times 4} {3 \times 4} \\ &= \dfrac {63} {12}, \quad \dfrac {66} {12}, \quad \dfrac {68} {12} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $\dfrac {68} {12} = \dfrac {17} {3} = \dfrac {1} {3} \ \text {of} \ 17$ is the biggest.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $\dfrac {1} {3} \ \text {of} \ 17$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                csse--11-plus--maths--2015--sample-paper-2.toml

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                rag_nj_pr

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  A full sweet jar weighs $165.5 \ \text{g}$. The jar contains $90$ sweets. Each sweet weighs $450\ \text{mg}$. How much does the empty jar weigh?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  It is really important to use the right units in calculations and convert where required.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  The weight of sweets is given in $\text{mg}$ while the weight of jar is given in $\text{g}$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Let's convert the sweets weight into $\text{g}$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} \text {Total weight of sweets} &= 90 \times 450 \ \text {mg} \\ &= 90 \times \dfrac {450}{1000} \text {g} \\ &= 90 \times 0.45 \\ &= 40.5 \ \text {g} \\ \text {Weight of empty jar } &= 162.5 - 40.5 \\ &= 122 \ \text {g} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $122 \ \text {g}$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  devonport-high-school-for-boys--11-plus--maths--2016--sample-paper-1.toml

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} \text {one} &= 1024 - 137 \\ &= 887 \\ \text {two} &= 887 - 137 \\ &= 750 \\ \text {three} &= 750 - 137 \\ &= 613 \\ \text {four} &= 613 - 137 \\ &= 476 \\ \text {five} &= 476 - 137 \\ &= 339 \\ \text {six} &= 339 - 137 \\ &= 202 \\ \text {seven} &= 202 - 137 \\ &= 65 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $137$ can be subtracted seven times from $1024$ before we get zero.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  I buy $11$ chocolate bars costing $27 \text{p}$ each. How much change would I get from $\pounds 5$?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  It is really important to use the right units in calculations and convert where required. Let's convert all the costs into $\pounds$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} \text {Cost of chocolate Bars} &= 11 \times 27 \ \text{p} \\ &= 11 \times \pounds \dfrac {27} {100} \\ &= 11 \times \pounds 0.27 \\ &= \pounds 2.97 \\ \text {Change recieved} &= 5 - 2.97 \\ &= \pounds 2.03 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $\pounds 2.03$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  A full sweet jar weighs $180.5\ \text{g}$.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   It is really important to use the right units in calculations and convert where required.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  The weight of sweets is given in $\text{mg}$ while the weight of jar is given in $\text{g}$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Let's convert the sweets weight into $\text{g}$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} \text {Total weight of sweets} &= 120 \times 450 \ \text{mg} \\ &= 120 \times \dfrac {450}{1000} \text {g} \\ &= 120 \times 0.45 \\ &= 54 \ \text {g} \\ \text {Weight of empty jar } &= 180.5 - 54 \\ &= 126.5 \ \text {g} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $126.5 \ \text {g}$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  A medicine bottle contains $90$ pills. Each pill weighs $250 \ \text{mg}$, The full bottle weighs $160 \ \text{g}$. How much does the empty bottle weigh?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  It is really important to use the right units in calculations and convert where required.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  The weight of pills is given in $\text{mg}$ while the weight of the bottle is given in $\text{g}$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Let's convert the pills weight to $\text{g}$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} \text {Total weight of pills} &= 90 \times 250 \ \text{mg} \\ &= 90 \times \dfrac {250}{1000} \ \text {g} \\ &= 90 \times 0.25 \\ &= 22.5 \ \text {g} \\ \text {Weight of empty bottle} &= 160 - 22.5 \\ &= 137.5 \ \text {g} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $137.5 \ \text {g}$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  devonport-high-school-for-boys--11-plus--maths--2018--sample-paper-3.toml

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  A full sweet jar weighs $180.5 \ \text{g}$. The jar contains $120$ sweets. Each sweet weighs $450 \ \text{mg}$. How much does the empty jar weigh?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  It is really important to use the right units in calculations and convert where required.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  The weight of sweets is given in $\text{mg}$ while the weight of the jar is given in $\text{g}$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Let's convert the sweets weight to $\text{g}$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} \text {Total weight of sweets} &= 120 \times 450 \ \text{mg} \\ &= 120 \times \dfrac {450}{1000} \ \text {g} \\ &= 120 \times 0.45 \\ &= 54 \ \text {g} \\ \text {Weight of empty jar } &= 180.5 - 54 \\ &= 126.5 \ \text {g} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $126.5 \ \text {g}$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              • $2019 - 567$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $ \begin{array}{ccccc} & 2 & 0 & 1 & 9 \ {}- & & 5 & 6 & 7 \ \hline & 1 & 4 & 5 & 2 \end{array} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $1452$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                • $67 \times 89$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{array}{cccc} & & 6 & 7 \ {} & \times & 8 & 9 \ \hline & 6 & 0 & 3 \ 5 & 3 & 6 & 0 \ \hline 5 & 9 & 6 & 3 \end{array} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $5963$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  • $81.9 \div 6$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $ \begin{aligned} & 81.9 \div 6 \\ &= \dfrac {819} {10} \div 6 \\ &= \dfrac {8190} {100} \times \dfrac {1} {6} \\ &= \dfrac {1365 \times 6} {100} \times \dfrac {1} {6} \\ &= \dfrac {1365 \times \cancel {6}} {100} \times \dfrac {1} {\cancel {6}} \\ &= \dfrac {1365} {100} \\ &= 13.65 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          Add brackets to this calculation to that the answer is $5$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $22 - 10 + 8 \div 4$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          • $22 -(10 + 8) \div 4$
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          • $(22 - 10) + 8 \div 4$
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          • $(22 - 10 + 8) \div 4$
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          • $22 - 10 + (8 \div 4)$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $ \begin{aligned} &\text {A.} \quad 22 - (10 + 8)\div 4 = 17.5 \not = 5 \\ &\text {B.} \quad (22 - 10) + 8 \div 4 = 14 \not = 5 \\ &\text {C.} \quad (22 - 10 + 8) \div 4 = 5 \\ &\text {D.} \quad 22 - 10 + (8 \div 4) = 14 \not = 5 \end{aligned} $
